tects you against calculation errors, unexpected bad news, or just being wrong."}],["$","div",null,{"style":{"borderTop":"1px solid var(--line)","paddingTop":12},"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"t-body","style":{"fontSize":"0.875rem","fontStyle":"italic","color":"var(--ink)","lineHeight":1.6,"marginBottom":6},"children":["“","The margin of safety is always dependent on the price paid. It will be large at one price, small at some higher price, nonexistent at some still higher price.","”"]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"t-micro","children":"Benjamin Graham, The Intelligent Investor"}]]}]]}]]}],["$","details","mr-market",{"className":"card","style":{"borderLeft":"3px solid var(--bear)","padding":0},"children":[["$","summary",null,{"style":{"padding":"16px","cursor":"pointer","listStyle":"none","display":"flex","justifyContent":"space-between","alignItems":"flex-start","gap":12,"minHeight":44},"children":[["$","div",null,{"style":{"flex":1},"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"t-body","style":{"fontWeight":700,"color":"var(--bear)"},"children":"Mr. Market"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"t-micro","style":{"marginTop":2},"children":"Graham's emotional market metaphor"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"style":{"color":"var(--muted)","fontSize":"0.75rem","fontFamily":"var(--font-mono)","marginTop":2,"flexShrink":0},"children":"▾"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"style":{"padding":"0 16px 16px","borderTop":"1px solid var(--line)"},"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"t-body","style":{"marginTop":14,"lineHeight":1.6},"children":"Imagine the stock market as a moody business partner who offers to buy or sell your stake every day — at wildly irrational prices. Your job is to exploit his mood swings, not follow them."}],["$","div",null,{"style":{"background":"var(--bg-hover)","padding":"10px 12px","margin":"12px 0","borderLeft":"2px solid var(--bear)"},"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"t-micro","style":{"color":"var(--bear)","marginBottom":4},"children":"HOW TO APPLY"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"t-body","style":{"fontSize":"0.875rem","color":"var(--muted)"},"children":"Mr. Market today: see the Fear & Greed dial on the Pulse screen for his current mood."}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"t-body","style":{"fontSize":"0.875rem","color":"var(--muted)","lineHeight":1.6,"marginBottom":12},"children":"When Mr. Market is panicked (Fear & Greed below 25), prices are often irrationally low — that is when Graham and Buffett buy. When he is euphoric (above 75), prices are often irrationally high — that is when they hold cash. The key: you never have to trade with him. You only trade when his price is better than fair."}],"$L1d"]}]]}],"$L1e","$L1f","$L20"]}]
1b:["$","div",null,{"className":"card","style":{"background":"var(--bear-10)","borderColor":"var(--bear)","marginBottom":"var(--gap)"},"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"t-micro","style":{"color":"var(--bear)","marginBottom":6},"children":"THE BRUTAL TRUTH"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"t-body","style":{"color":"var(--bear)","fontSize":"0.8rem","lineHeight":1.6},"children":"~90% of day traders lose money within the first year. ~80% quit within 2 years. The 10% who survive share four traits: they risk 1-2% per trade, they journal every trade, they have a defined edge, and they understand that psychology is 80% of the game. This school exists to put you in the 10%."}]]}]
